ation. It manages significant newlines and complex f-string interpolations, providing a clean foundation. The AST module acts as the central data hub, providing a representation of the program using a highly efficient \"Kind + Data\" pattern. Crucially, it features a generative desugaring engine that expands high-level syntactic sugar—such as relations, interface fields, and default implementations—into fundamental constructs before semantic analysis. It also selectively merges the standard library based on reachability analysis.\n\nThe checker assumes responsibility for all semantic rules, acting as the semantic truth of the compiler. It performs a multi-pass analysis for type inference, scope management, module import resolution, and validation. It handles structural subtyping, numeric widening, optional wrapping, and enforces concurrency safety through guarded annotations. Ultimately, it annotates the AST with resolved types. \n\nThe LIR module then takes this semantically rich tree and bridges the gap to the backends. It enforces structured control flow and flat expressions, assigning every sub-expression to a unique temporary variable. This crucial step removes the burden of semantic resolution from the backends. The LIR pipeline includes optimization passes for side-effect elimination and multi-return destructuring, as well as a comprehensive monomorphization pass to specialize generic types and functions for targets that lack native generics. Finally, the backends act as thin emitters that translate the simplified LIR into idiomatic target source code. The C backend relies heavily on the runtime module, which provides a foundational C header library establishing the memory layout and operational semantics for Forge's high-level constructs.\n\nIn parallel to the compilation pipeline, the verifier module operates as a standalone structural integrity engine. It parses `.forge` specification files and performs a deep structural comparison against the actual Go implementation, utilizing the Go standard library's AST tools to extract type information. It normalizes naming conventions across the two systems and performs a reverse completeness check to ensure every exported Go symbol is documented. This ensures that the documented design and the codebase remain perfectly synchronized, enforcing the philosophy that documentation should be an active, verifiable contract rather than a passive artifact.\n","file_path":"project-design.md"}}}]},{"role":"user","parts":[{"functionResponse":{"name":"write_file","response":{"result":"✅ **File Created Successfully**\n\n**File**: `/Users/bill/projects/forge/project-design.md`\n**Size**: 4316 bytes\n**Permissions**: -rw-r--r--\n**Lines**: 18\n**Duration**: 0.00s\n"}}}]}],"generationConfig":{"temperature":0.3,"maxOutputTokens":8192,"thinkingConfig":{"thinking_level":"high"}},"safetySettings":[{"category":"HARM_CATEGORY_DANGEROUS_CONTENT","threshold":"BLOCK_NONE"},{"category":"HARM_CATEGORY_HATE_SPEECH","threshold":"BLOCK_NONE"},{"category":"HARM_CATEGORY_HARASSMENT","threshold":"BLOCK_NONE"},{"category":"HARM_CATEGORY_SEXUALLY_EXPLICIT","threshold":"BLOCK_NONE"},{"category":"HARM_CATEGORY_CIVIC_INTEGRITY","threshold":"BLOCK_NONE"}],"cachedContent":"cachedContents/lxaqxj1o3alue4di2euv9y7vwoevn0aq2w7yuzca"}
