{"chunk":{"candidates":[{"content":{"role":"model","parts":[{"thoughtSignature":"EnYKdAEMOdbHNmZFe7vQuIoorXYW1WA4e89QCPE/G0yId5XtN9elmMAcCLvC/XVdRFI2Lm8R7UwU0mMj/zhjuHpH7jmL5TTRpcPZ6bO9+pdAhLQeAx8jHkCbg0XHMr4kz9REf9u3L472CuoR93gjIhlu1S5oRl0D","functionCall":{"name":"write_file","args":{"append":true,"content":"\n## Interface \u0026 Contract Map\n\nThe system's boundaries are primarily defined by the rich data structures passed between modules rather than traditional Go interfaces. These data structures act as the fundamental contracts that govern module interactions, ensuring a decoupled and data-driven architecture.\n\nThe most critical contract is the Abstract Syntax Tree. The `ast.File` and its constituent nodes representing declarations, expressions, and statements form the central nervous system of the compiler. The parser module acts as the initial producer of this contract, transforming source code into the raw AST. The AST module itself acts as both a consumer and producer, taking the raw AST and producing a desugared version where high-level constructs are flattened. The checker module consumes this desugared AST for semantic analysis and mutates it by attaching resolved type information to the `ResolvedType` and `InferredTypeArgs` fields. The LIR module consumes the fully type-checked AST to generate the intermediate representation. Additionally, the verifier module consumes the AST of `.forge` files to compare against Go source code.\n\nThe Type Registry contract, defined by the `checker.Registry` and `checker.Type` structures, represents the semantic truth of the program. The checker module builds and populates this registry during its declaration and checking passes, resolving all cross-module dependencies and generic constraints. The LIR module is the primary consumer of this contract, relying heavily on the type registry and resolved types to correctly lower high-level constructs, such as generics, classes, and enums, into low-level operations.\n\nThe LIR contract, represented by the `lir.LProgram`, defines the fully resolved and flattened program state. The LIR module's lowerer produces this representation, ensuring that all expressions are flattened into temporaries and control flow is structured. Internal optimization and monomorphization passes within the LIR module consume and mutate this structure, specializing generic types and eliminating redundant operations. Ultimately, the backends consume the optimized `LProgram` to emit the final source code.\n\nThe Runtime contract is defined by the C runtime header (`forge_runtime.h`), which establishes the execution environment for C-compiled Forge programs. The runtime module provides these foundational macros and inline functions, defining the memory layout for dynamic slices, strings, optional types, error results, and tagged unions. The C backend within the LIR module acts as the sole consumer, emitting code that relies entirely on this contract for operational semantics and concurrency primitives.\n","file_path":"project-design.md"}}}]},"finishReason":""}],"usageMetadata":{"promptTokenCount":25000,"candidatesTokenCount":532,"totalTokenCount":25546,"cachedContentTokenCount":24157}},"chunk_number":1}
