{"contents":[{"role":"model","parts":[{"thoughtSignature":"EqIBCp8BAQw51sfKcewM9QjT6OeWrEErDeqXbz2sid2BPCPZ/zCDtjCt6X8rwPuECYTdXBtJMvvpHqw5TIbFVsPhqBZoAPEOLkw7PeOttlS6IRAb/SF5zoxsAIyO4RfpFFS+ze1jQyl5t2MPAX90JbnjnUuprBlbNlnOlYotQUiyx7GLhOpJxbe9ZgvIkvmYsdv1jqlgdA0bdShhYQwEUc/4oOQ1","functionCall":{"name":"read_file","args":{"file_path":"runtime/design.md"}}}]},{"role":"user","parts":[{"text":"# Task: Synthesize Project Architecture\n\nPlease synthesize a high-level `project-design.md` by analyzing the individual `design.md` files from all modules. This document will be our primary map for navigating this project in the future.\n\n## IMPORTANT: Existing Documentation Found\n\nAn existing `project-design.md` was found at the project root. **You MUST read it first.**\nYour goal is to **upgrade and improve** this document, not degrade it. Preserve its depth, architectural insights, and specific details while incorporating new information from the module designs.\n\n## Project Context\n\n- Project Path: /Users/bill/projects/forge\n- Total Modules: 6\n\n## Modules to Analyze\n\n- ast: pkg/ast/design.md\n- checker: pkg/checker/design.md\n- lir: pkg/lir/design.md\n- parser: pkg/parser/design.md\n- verifier: pkg/verifier/design.md\n- runtime: runtime/design.md\n\n## Your Strategy\n\n1. **Read Existing Design**: Read the current `project-design.md` at the root.\n2. **Read Module Designs**: Read the `design.md` file for every module listed above.\n3. **Identify Gaps**: Compare the existing project design with the new module-level details.\n4. **Upgrade Narrative**: Synthesize a superior `project-design.md` that preserves the best of the old while adding the precision of the new.\n5. **Module Map**: Include a **categorized tree view** of all modules, with each entry being a **clickable markdown link** to its `design.md` file (e.g., `[pkg/scanner](pkg/scanner/design.md)`).\n6. **Use Tools**: Use `write_file` and `edit_file` to build the document in sections. Do NOT output the whole document at once.\n\nWhen finished, confirm: 'Project documentation complete.'\n"}]},{"role":"user","parts":[{"functionResponse":{"name":"read_file","response":{"result":"[ID: tool_680553d570bc0199]\nFile: /Users/bill/projects/forge/runtime/design.md (118 lines)\n\n# Runtime Module Design\n\n## Executive Summary\n\nThe `runtime` module provides the foundational C runtime library required by the Forge compiler's C backend. It is implemented as a passive, header-only library that establishes the memory layout and operational semantics for Forge's high-level constructs in a C environment. By providing a suite of macros and inline functions, the runtime enables the C backend to transform complex Forge features—such as dynamic slices, length-prefixed strings, optional types, error results, tagged unions, and concurrency primitives—into efficient and readable C code. Its primary goal is to bridge the gap between Forge's expressive type system and C's low-level primitives while maintaining semantic equivalence and providing a robust execution environment.\n\n## File Inventory\n\n- [forge_runtime.h](forge_runtime.h): The core runtime header. It contains all macro definitions, type structures, and inline helper functions that constitute the Forge execution environment for C targets. It defines the fundamental data structures for slices, strings, optionals, and results, as well as the logic for concurrency and file I/O.\n\n## Architecture and Data Flow\n\nThe `runtime` module is a passive component that does not maintain internal state or have an independent execution flow. Instead, it acts as a contract and a toolkit for the code generated by the [LIR module](../pkg/lir/design.md).\n\nThe architecture leverages C macros to implement a form of \"template-based\" type generation. Since C lacks native support for generics, the Forge C backend uses these macros to define concrete, specialized struct types for every unique instantiation of a generic Forge type (e.g., `Slice_int32_t`, `Opt_string`, or `Chan_int32_t`). This approach ensures type safety at the C level and allows the compiler to generate code that is tailored to specific data types. Data flows through these structures as they are passed between functions, with the runtime providing the logic for common operations like resizing slices, wrapping values in optional containers, or managing thread-safe communication through channels.\n\n## Interface Implementations\n\nAs a C header library, this module does not implement any Go interfaces. It serves as the target execution environment for the C code generator within the [LIR module](../pkg/lir/design.md).\n\n## Public API\n\nThe Public API of the runtime consists of the macros and inline functions intended to be utilized by the Forge-generated C code. These are categorized by the Forge language features they support.\n\n### Dynamic Slices\nForge slices are implemented as dynamic arrays with automatic resizing capabilities and support for sub-slicing.\n- `FORGE_SLICE_DEF(ElemType, SliceName)`: A macro that defines a struct containing a pointer to the data, the current length, and the total capacity.\n- `forge_slice_empty(SliceName)`: Initializes a slice structure to an empty state (null data, zero length and capacity).\n- `forge_push(slice_ptr, elem, SliceName)`: Appends an element to the slice. If the length reaches the capacity, it performs a geometric resize (doubling the capacity) using `realloc`.\n- `forge_pop(slice_ptr)`: Removes and returns the last element of the slice. The caller is responsible for ensuring the slice is not empty.\n- `forge_subslice(slice, low, high, SliceName)`: Creates a new slice view representing the range `[low, high)`. This view shares the underlying data pointer with the original slice.\n- `forge_slice_lit(SliceName, ElemType, ...)`: A convenience macro that creates a new slice from a C initializer list, allocating heap memory for the contents.\n- `forge_contains(slice, elem)`: Performs a linear search through the slice to determine if a specific element is present.\n\n### Strings\nStrings in Forge are implemented as length-prefixed byte slices (`forge_string`), which is an alias for `ForgeSlice_uint8_t`. This allows strings to contain embedded null bytes and ensures that length-related operations are O(1).\n- `FORGE_STR(lit)`: A macro to create a `forge_string` from a C string literal at compile-time.\n- `forge_str_from_cstr(cstr)`: Creates a `forge_string` from a null-terminated C string, copying the data to the heap.\n- `forge_str_from_bytes(data, len)`: Creates a `forge_string` from raw bytes, copying them to the heap and adding a hidden trailing null for C interop.\n- `forge_str_eq(a, b)`: Performs a length-aware equality check.\n- `forge_str_cmp(a, b)`: Performs a lexicographic comparison.\n- `forge_str_concat(a, b)`: Concatenates two strings into a new heap-allocated `forge_string`.\n- `forge_str_contains`, `forge_str_index_of`, `forge_str_has_prefix`, `forge_str_has_suffix`: Length-aware string searching and prefix/suffix checks.\n- `forge_str_replace`, `forge_str_repeat`, `forge_str_join`: High-level string transformations that return new heap-allocated strings.\n- `forge_str_trim`: Returns a new string with leading and trailing whitespace removed.\n- `forge_fprint_str(file, s)`: Writes a `forge_string` to a `FILE*` in a length-aware manner.\n\n### Optional Types\nOptional types (`T?`) are represented as a struct containing a boolean flag (`has`) and the actual value.\n- `FORGE_OPT_DEF(ElemType, OptName)`: Defines a specialized optional struct for a given type.\n- `forge_some(value, OptName)`: Wraps a concrete value into an optional struct with the `has` flag set to true.\n- `forge_none(OptName)`: Returns an optional struct with the `has` flag set to false.\n- `forge_isnull(opt)`: A helper to check if an optional value is empty.\n- `forge_unwrap(opt)`: Extracts the value from an optional. This should only be called after verifying the value exists.\n\n### Error Results\nForge's idiomatic `(T, error)` return pattern is mapped to a result struct in C.\n- `FORGE_RESULT_DEF(ElemType, ResultName)`: Defines a result struct containing a success value, an error message (`const char*`), and a boolean `is_err` flag.\n- `forge_ok(val, ResultName)`: Constructs a successful result containing the provided value.\n- `forge_err(msg, ResultName)`: Constructs an error result containing the provided error message.\n- `forge_is_err(r)`: Checks if a result represents a failure.\n\n### Concurrency Primitives\nThe runtime provides support for Forge's concurrency model using POSIX threads (pthreads).\n- `FORGE_CHAN_DEF(ElemType, ChanName)`: Defines a thread-safe, buffered or unbuffered channel structure.\n- `FORGE_CHAN_IMPL(ElemType, ChanName, Suffix)`: Generates the implementation functions for a specific channel type, including `make`, `send`, `recv`, `close`, and `free`.\n- `forge_spawn(func, arg)`: Launches a function in a new detached thread, implementing the Forge `spawn` keyword.\n\n### Utility Helpers\n- `forge_hash_string`: Implements the FNV-1a hashing algorithm for strings.\n- `forge_sprintf`: A wrapper around `vsnprintf` that automatically calculates the required size and returns a heap-allocated formatted string.\n- `forge_bool_str`: Returns \"true\" or \"false\" for a boolean value.\n- `forge_toupper`, `forge_tolower`: Convert strings to upper or lower case, returning new heap-allocated strings.\n- `forge_char_to_string`: Converts a single character (uint8_t) to a heap-allocated string.\n- `forge_read_file`: Reads an entire file into a heap-allocated string, returning a `forge_str_bool_t` struct.\n- `forge_write_file`: Writes a string to a file, returning a boolean indicating success.\n- `forge_getwd`: Returns the current working directory.\n- `forge_path_dir`, `forge_path_base`, `forge_path_ext`: Utilities for working with file paths.\n- `forge_itoa`: Converts an `int64_t` to a heap-allocated string.\n- `forge_atoi`: Parses a string into an `int64_t`, returning a `forge_atoi_result` struct.\n- `forge_parse_float`: Parses a string into a `double`, returning a `forge_parse_float_result` struct.\n\n### Tagged Unions\nFor ad-hoc union types (e.g., `string | i32`), the runtime provides a generic `ForgeUnion` struct.\n- `ForgeUnion`: A struct containing an integer tag and a union of supported Forge types (i32, i64, f32, f64, bool, string, and pointers).\n- `FORGE_UNION_TAG_*`: Constants for identifying the active member of a `ForgeUnion`.\n- `forge_union_i32`, `forge_union_string`, etc.: Specialized constructor functions that initialize a `ForgeUnion` with the correct tag and value.\n\n## Implementation Details\n\n### Memory Management\nThe runtime currently utilizes the standard C library's `malloc`, `realloc`, and `free` for memory management. A critical implementation detail is that the runtime does not yet include a garbage collector. Consequently, heap-allocated objects—including slices, strings created by helper functions, and class instances—are currently leaked during execution. This is a known limitation that is acceptable for short-lived compiler tasks but will require a GC (such as Boehm-Demers-Weiser) for broader use.\n\n### Slice Growth Strategy\nThe `forge_push` macro implements a geometric growth strategy to ensure amortized O(1) append operations. When a slice's length reaches its capacity, the capacity is doubled. If the slice was previously empty, it is initialized with a default capacity of 4. This minimizes the number of reallocations required as a slice grows.\n\n### String Handling\nStrings in the Forge C runtime are represented by the `forge_string` struct, which contains a pointer to the data and its length. This design allows for O(1) length retrieval and supports strings with embedded null bytes. For compatibility with standard C functions that expect null-terminated strings, heap-allocated `forge_string` objects carry a hidden trailing `\\0` byte immediately following the data. This trailing byte is not included in the `.len` field.\n\n### Concurrency Implementation\nChannels are implemented using a circular buffer protected by a `pthread_mutex_t`. Two condition variables (`not_empty` and `not_full`) are used to manage blocking send and receive operations. `forge_spawn` uses `pthread_create` and `pthread_detach` to provide fire-and-forget thread execution.\n\n### Tagged Union Dispatch\nThe `ForgeUnion` type uses an integer tag to identify the active member of its internal union. This allows the generated C code to perform safe type dispatching (e.g., in `match` statements) by checking the tag before accessing the union's data.\n\n## Dependencies\n\n- **Standard C Library**: The runtime depends on standard headers including `\u003cstdio.h\u003e`, `\u003cstdlib.h\u003e`, `\u003cstdint.h\u003e`, `\u003cstdbool.h\u003e`, `\u003cstring.h\u003e`, `\u003cstdarg.h\u003e`, `\u003cctype.h\u003e`, and `\u003cunistd.h\u003e`.\n- **POSIX Threads**: The concurrency primitives require the `pthread` library.\n- **LIR Module**: This module is a critical dependency for the C backend in [pkg/lir](../pkg/lir/design.md), which relies on the macros and types defined here to emit valid C code.\n\n## Technical Debt and Future Work\n\n- **Garbage Collection**: Integrating a garbage collector is the highest priority to prevent memory leaks in long-running Forge programs compiled to C.\n- **Map Implementation**: A robust hash map implementation is required to support Forge's `map\u003cK, V\u003e` type in the C backend.\n- **Error Handling Refinement**: The current error result uses a simple string for error messages. This should be expanded to support more complex, structured error types as the language evolves.\n- **Thread Safety**: While channels are thread-safe, other runtime primitives (like slices) are not and will require synchronization if shared across threads.\n"}}}]}],"tools":[{"functionDeclarations":[{"name":"handoff_task","description":"Write a handoff document for a fresh instance of yourself to continue your current work. Called automatically when context is nearly full, but you can also call it proactively.\n\nThe next instance starts with ZERO context and will read ONLY what you specify here. Anything you don't include is permanently lost.","parameters":{"properties":{"critical_context":{"description":"Any decisions, user preferences, failed approaches, or context not captured in files. If the user told you to do something a specific way, include that here.","type":"string"},"files_to_read":{"description":"Every file path (with optional line ranges) the next instance should read to have the context it needs. Be thorough.","items":{"description":"","properties":{"end_line":{"description":"Optional: End line number.","type":"number"},"path":{"description":"File path relative to project root.","type":"string"},"reason":{"description":"Why the next instance needs this file.","type":"string"},"start_line":{"description":"Optional: Start line number.","type":"number"}},"required":["path"],"type":"object"},"type":"array"},"memory":{"description":"Session memories to preserve: what was built, key decisions made with rationale, things considered and rejected, observations, and any insights worth keeping. This is automatically appended to today's daily memory log (~/.cr/memory/YYYY-MM-DD.md).","type":"string"},"plan":{"description":"Your remaining steps, in order.","type":"string"},"summary":{"description":"What task you're working on, what's been accomplished, and what remains.","type":"string"}},"required":["summary","memory"],"type":"object"}},{"name":"refine_context","description":"Discard or trim previous tool outputs to free up context. Use the ID found at the start of each tool output.","parameters":{"properties":{"edits":{"description":"List of tool outputs to refine.","items":{"description":"","properties":{"id":{"description":"The ID string found at the start of the tool output (e.g., 'tool_8675309').","type":"string"},"keep":{"description":"Line ranges to keep (e.g., '1-50, 100-120'). If omitted/empty, the entire output is discarded.","type":"string"}},"required":["id"],"type":"object"},"type":"array"}},"required":["edits"],"type":"object"}},{"name":"copy_file","description":"Copy a file to a new location. Useful for backups, templates, duplicating content.","parameters":{"properties":{"destination":{"description":"Destination file path","type":"string"},"overwrite":{"description":"Whether to overwrite if destination exists (default: false)","type":"boolean"},"source":{"description":"Source file path","type":"string"}},"required":["source","destination"],"type":"object"}},{"name":"delete_file","description":"Delete a file. Use with caution - this cannot be undone.","parameters":{"properties":{"confirm":{"description":"Must be true to confirm deletion","type":"boolean"},"file_path":{"description":"Path to file to delete","type":"string"}},"required":["file_path","confirm"],"type":"object"}},{"name":"edit_file","description":"Make targeted edits to an existing file using find and replace. Perfect for code modifications.\n\n**For multiple edits**: Make multiple separate edit_file calls in one response rather than using a single call. This keeps formatting clean, avoids escaping issues, and makes each edit independently verifiable.","parameters":{"properties":{"file_path":{"description":"Path to the existing file to edit (e.g., 'src/main.go', '../config/settings.json')","type":"string"},"new_text":{"description":"Replacement text to substitute for the old_text (e.g., updated function code, corrected variable name)","type":"string"},"old_text":{"description":"Exact text to find (must match exactly, including whitespace)","type":"string"}},"required":["file_path","old_text","new_text"],"type":"object"}},{"name":"list_directory","description":"List files and directories. Shows file sizes, types, and modification times for better context.\n\n**Size Limits**: Output is truncated at approximately 16KB by default (configurable via max_items) to protect context window.\n\nReturns: Structured list of files and directories with sizes, permissions, and timestamps.","parameters":{"properties":{"directory":{"description":"Directory path to list (default: current directory)","type":"string"},"exclude_dirs":{"description":"Comma-separated directories to exclude (default: node_modules,.git,.hg). Prevents traversing heavy directories.","type":"string"},"max_depth":{"description":"Maximum recursion depth (default: 10). Limits how deep to traverse subdirectories.","type":"number"},"max_items":{"description":"Maximum items to return (default: 500). Prevents context overflow on large directories while staying within the 16KB output limit.","type":"number"},"recursive":{"description":"Recursively list subdirectories (default: false)","type":"boolean"},"show_hidden":{"description":"Include hidden files and directories (default: false)","type":"boolean"}},"required":[],"type":"object"}},{"name":"move_file","description":"Move or rename a file. Atomic operation within same filesystem.","parameters":{"properties":{"destination":{"description":"Destination file path","type":"string"},"overwrite":{"description":"Whether to overwrite if destination exists (default: false)","type":"boolean"},"source":{"description":"Source file path","type":"string"}},"required":["source","destination"],"type":"object"}},{"name":"read_file","description":"Read the contents of a file. Returns the full file content with line numbers for easy reference.\n\n**Size Limits**: Content is truncated at 64KB by default (configurable via text_limit) to protect context window. Use line ranges for large files.","parameters":{"properties":{"end_line":{"description":"Optional: Stop reading at this line number (inclusive)\nDefault: Read to end of file","type":"number"},"file_path":{"description":"Path to the file to read (relative or absolute)","type":"string"},"max_line_len":{"description":"Optional: Maximum length for individual lines (default: 2000). Lines longer than this are truncated with '...' to prevent log files with very long lines from overwhelming context.","type":"number"},"start_line":{"description":"Optional: Start reading from this line number (1-indexed)\nDefault: Read from beginning of file","type":"number"},"text_limit":{"description":"Optional: Maximum number of characters to read in one operation (default: 65536 = 64KB). Protects against reading massive files that could overflow the context window.","type":"number"}},"required":["file_path"],"type":"object"}},{"name":"write_file","description":"Create or completely overwrite a file with new content. Use edit_file for modifications to existing files.","parameters":{"properties":{"append":{"description":"Optional: If true, append content to the end of the file instead of overwriting. Default: false.","type":"boolean"},"content":{"description":"Complete content to write to the file","type":"string"},"file_path":{"description":"Path where the file should be created/written","type":"string"}},"required":["file_path","content"],"type":"object"}},{"name":"find_files","description":"Find files by name pattern. Like the Unix 'find' command but simpler.\n\n**Use Cases**: Locate files by name, find all JSON files, discover campaign content.","parameters":{"properties":{"directory":{"description":"Directory to search in (default: current directory)","type":"string"},"include_hidden":{"description":"Include hidden files/directories (default: false)","type":"boolean"},"max_depth":{"description":"Maximum directory depth to search (default: 10)","type":"number"},"pattern":{"description":"Glob pattern to match filenames (e.g., '*.md', 'monster_*.json', '*vampire*')","type":"string"}},"required":["pattern"],"type":"object"}},{"name":"search_files","description":"Search for text patterns across files (like grep). Returns matches with line numbers and context.\n\n**Use Cases**: Find all mentions of a variable, locate specific text, search campaign content.\n\n**Size Limits**: Results truncated at 32KB to protect context window.","parameters":{"properties":{"case_sensitive":{"description":"Whether search is case-sensitive (default: false)","type":"boolean"},"context_lines":{"description":"Number of context lines before and after match (default: 2)","type":"number"},"directory":{"description":"Directory to search in (default: current directory)","type":"string"},"file_pattern":{"description":"Glob pattern for files to search (e.g., '*.md', '*.go', '*.json'). Default: all text files","type":"string"},"max_matches":{"description":"Maximum number of matches to return (default: 100)","type":"number"},"pattern":{"description":"Text or regex pattern to search for (e.g., 'function.*handle', 'TODO:', 'vampire')","type":"string"}},"required":["pattern"],"type":"object"}},{"name":"semantic_search","description":"Intelligently search for code concepts, patterns, and functionality across your codebase. Unlike grep, this understands code meaning and context. Returns results with token counts for AI context management.\n\n**Size Limits**: Results are truncated at approximately 32KB by default (configurable via max_tokens) to protect context window.","parameters":{"properties":{"directory":{"description":"Directory to search in (default: current directory)","type":"string"},"include_extensions":{"description":"Comma-separated file extensions to include (e.g., '.go,.js,.py')\nDefault: Search all text files","type":"string"},"max_results":{"description":"Maximum number of results to return (default: 10)","type":"number"},"max_tokens":{"description":"Maximum tokens to return to fit AI context window (default: 8000)","type":"number"},"query":{"description":"What you're looking for (e.g., 'error handling', 'user authentication', 'database connection')","type":"string"}},"required":["query"],"type":"object"}}]}],"generationConfig":{"temperature":0.3,"maxOutputTokens":8192,"thinkingConfig":{"thinking_level":"high"}},"safetySettings":[{"category":"HARM_CATEGORY_DANGEROUS_CONTENT","threshold":"BLOCK_NONE"},{"category":"HARM_CATEGORY_HATE_SPEECH","threshold":"BLOCK_NONE"},{"category":"HARM_CATEGORY_HARASSMENT","threshold":"BLOCK_NONE"},{"category":"HARM_CATEGORY_SEXUALLY_EXPLICIT","threshold":"BLOCK_NONE"},{"category":"HARM_CATEGORY_CIVIC_INTEGRITY","threshold":"BLOCK_NONE"}],"systemInstruction":{"role":"system","parts":[{"text":"You are a documentation scout agent.\n\n---\n\n## 📁 File Operations\n\n**Size Limits**: File content is truncated at 64KB by default (configurable via text_limit). Directory listings truncated at 16KB (500 items max).\n\n- **read_file**: Read files with line numbers. Use line ranges for large files.\n- **write_file**: Create or overwrite files. Use `append: true` to append.\n- **edit_file**: Find-and-replace edits. Make multiple separate edit_file calls for multiple edits in one response — keeps formatting clean and each edit independently verifiable.\n- **list_directory**: Browse directories with sizes, types, and timestamps.\n- **copy_file**: Copy a file to a new location. Useful for backups and templates.\n- **move_file**: Move or rename a file. Atomic within same filesystem.\n- **delete_file**: Delete a file (requires `confirm: true`). Cannot be undone.\n\n**Large File Strategy**: Use line ranges, search tools, or split operations when files exceed the size limit.\n\n---\n\n## 🔍 Search Tools\n\n**Size Limits**: Search results truncated at 32KB by default.\n\n- **semantic_search**: Intelligently search for code concepts, patterns, and functionality across your codebase. Unlike grep, this understands code meaning and context. (8K tokens default)\n- **search_files**: Search for text patterns across files (like grep). Returns matches with line numbers and context.\n- **find_files**: Find files by name pattern. Like the Unix 'find' command but simpler.\n\n**When outputs are truncated**: Narrow the search directory, reduce max_results, or use more specific queries.\n\n---\n\n## 🧠 Context Management\n\n- **refine_context**: Discard or trim previous tool outputs to free up context. Use the ID found at the start of each tool output. Essential for long sessions where accumulated tool output fills the context window.\n- **handoff_task**: Write a handoff document for a fresh instance of yourself to continue your current work. Called automatically when context is nearly full, but you can also call it proactively. The next instance starts with ZERO context — include everything it needs.\n\n---\n\n# Global Scout - Project Synthesis\n\n## The CodeRhapsody Mission\n\nYou are part of a high-velocity partnership between Bill (waywardgeek) and the CodeRhapsody AI agents. Bill is a master architect who works at 750 wpm; we are the implementation engine. \n\nYour documentation is not a passive archive—it is the **active mental model** for the next agent who will enter this directory to build features. If your documentation is vague, the next agent fails. If your documentation is precise and architectural, we move at 10X speed. Write with the confidence and clarity of an expert who knows their work is the foundation of a 90K+ line innovation.\n\nYour mission is to synthesize a high-level architectural overview of an entire project into a single document named project-design.md.\n\nThese design documents are critical for our future productivity. When we work together in CodeRhapsody later, I will rely on these files to understand the system's \"big picture\" without having to re-read every source file. Your goal is to create a map that helps both humans and AI navigate the complexity of the system.\n\n## The Prose Mandate\n\nWrite your analysis in continuous, flowing prose. The user (Bill) listens to these documents via Text-to-Speech (TTS) at 750 WPM, and bulleted lists are highly disruptive to that experience. \n\n- **Use Narrative Prose**: For all architectural concepts, algorithms, module descriptions, and workflows, use full, descriptive sentences.\n- **Avoid Lists**: Do NOT use bulleted or numbered lists for technical descriptions. Lists should be reserved ONLY for simple inventories (like a list of file names or module names) where prose would be genuinely redundant.\n- **Simple Headers**: Use simple headers for organization.\n- **Clean Markdown**: Avoid excessive markdown syntax like deep nesting or heavy bolding.\n\nYour goal is a technical narrative that reads like a high-end architectural briefing, not a slide deck.\n\n## Your Role\n\nYou analyze the individual design.md files created for each module and synthesize them into a cohesive project-level narrative. You focus on the \"connective tissue\" of the system: how modules interact, shared design patterns, and the overall data flow.\n\n## Mandate for Depth\n\nDo not settle for a superficial overview. You have a 1,000,000+ token context window; use it to be thorough. A comprehensive `project-design.md` for a complex system should be a substantial document (often 10-20 pages if printed). If the project is 90K lines, your synthesis should reflect that scale. We value precision and architectural depth over brevity.\n\n## Output Structure\n\nCreate project-design.md at the root with the following narrative flow:\n\n1. **Executive Summary**: What is this project? Why does it exist? What are its primary goals?\n2. **System Architecture**: A deep narrative of the system's structure. How do the major components relate? Describe the \"philosophy\" of the architecture (e.g., hexagonal, layered, actor-based).\n3. **Interface \u0026 Contract Map**: A critical section describing the primary interfaces that define the system's boundaries. For each major interface, list which modules implement it and which modules consume it.\n4. **Module Map**: A detailed inventory of each module. For each, provide a multi-paragraph summary of its role, its internal state management, and the primary interfaces it implements or consumes.\n5. **Integration Patterns \u0026 Workflows**: How do modules communicate? Trace 2-3 of the most complex cross-module workflows in detail (e.g., \"From CLI command to AI response to file write\").\n6. **Dependency Overview**: A prose description of the project's dependency graph, layering, and any notable architectural constraints.\n\n## Guidelines\n\n- **Preserve Quality**: If a `project-design.md` already exists, read it first. Your goal is to improve and update it, not degrade it. If the existing documentation is already excellent and accurate, preserve its depth and clarity while incorporating new insights from the module designs.\n- **Be proportional**: The length of your synthesis must reflect the complexity of the project. A large project requires a deep, extensive narrative.\n- **Focus on utility**: Write what you would need to know to be productive in this codebase tomorrow.\n- **Interface Focus**: Pay special attention to how modules satisfy global interfaces (e.g., \"The database package implements the StorageInterface used by the API\").\n- **Use write_file and edit_file** to build the document in sections. Do not try to output the whole document in one tool call; build it section by section to ensure maximum detail.\n- When finished, simply confirm: Project documentation complete.\n\n---\n\n\n## File Management \u0026 Context Tools\n\nYou have access to safe file manipulation and context management tools:\n- **File Operations**: read_file, write_file, edit_file, copy_file, move_file, delete_file - Manage content\n- **Navigation**: list_directory - Explore directories  \n- **Search**: semantic_search, search_files, find_files - Find code/content by meaning or pattern\n- **Context Management**: refine_context - Trim large tool outputs to manage context\n\nAll file operations are restricted to your sandbox directory for security.\nThese tools enhance your primary function as defined above.\n"}]}}
